# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: api-versioning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] The term was introduced by American mathematician Benjamin Peirce in 1870 in the context of elements of algebras that remain invariant when raised to a positive integer power, and literally means "(the quality of having) the same power", from *idem* + *potence* (same + power).
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] If the set E has n elements, we can partition it into k chosen fixed points and $n-k$ non-fixed points under f , and then $k^{n-k}$ is the number of different idempotent functions.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] is the total number of possible idempotent functions on the set.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Neither idempotence nor non-idempotence is preserved under function composition.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] As an example for the former, $f(x)=x$ mod 3 and $g(x)=\max(x,5)$ are both idempotent, but $f\circ g$ is not, although $g\circ f$ happens to be.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] As an example for the latter, the negation function $\neg$ on the Boolean domain is not idempotent, but $\neg \circ \neg$ is.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Similarly, unary negation $-(\cdot )$ of real numbers is not idempotent, but $-(\cdot )\circ -(\cdot )$ is.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In both cases, the composition is simply the identity function, which is idempotent.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] A morphism $f:x\to x$ in a category is called *idempotent* if $f\circ f=f$ .
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] An idempotent is said to *split* if it can be written as $f=h\circ g$ for some $g:x\to y,\,h:y\to x$ with $g\circ h=\operatorname {id}$ .
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] A category is said to be idempotent complete if every idempotent splits.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] For example, ${\mathsf {Set}}$ is idempotent complete.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] This is a very useful property in many situations, as it means that an operation can be repeated or retried as often as necessary without causing unintended effects.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] With non-idempotent operations, the algorithm may have to keep track of whether the operation was already performed or not.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] A function looking up a customer's name and address in a database is typically idempotent, since this will not cause the database to change.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Similarly, a request for changing a customer's address to XYZ is typically idempotent, because the final address will be the same no matter how many times the request is submitted.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] However, a customer request for placing an order is typically not idempotent since multiple requests will lead to multiple orders being placed.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] A request for canceling a particular order is idempotent because no matter how many requests are made the order remains canceled.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] A sequence of idempotent subroutines where at least one subroutine is different from the others, however, is not necessarily idempotent if a later subroutine in the sequence changes a value that an earlier subroutine depends on—*idempotence is not closed under sequential composition*.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] For example, suppose the initial value of a variable is 3 and there is a subroutine sequence that reads the variable, then changes it to 5, and then reads it again.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Each step in the sequence is idempotent: both steps reading the variable have no side effects and the step changing the variable to 5 will always have the same effect no matter how many times it is executed.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Nonetheless, executing the entire sequence once produces the output (3, 5), but executing it a second time produces the output (5, 5), so the sequence is not idempotent.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), idempotence and safety are the major attributes that separate HTTP methods.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Of the major HTTP methods, GET, PUT, and DELETE should be implemented in an idempotent manner according to the standard, but POST doesn't need to be.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] GET retrieves the state of a resource; PUT updates the state of a resource; and DELETE deletes a resource.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] As in the example above, reading data usually has no side effects, so it is idempotent (in fact *nullipotent*).
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Updating and deleting a given data are each usually idempotent as long as the request uniquely identifies the resource and only that resource again in the future.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] PUT and DELETE with unique identifiers reduce to the simple case of assignment to a variable of either a value or the null-value, respectively, and are idempotent for the same reason; the end result is always the same as the result of the initial execution, even if the response differs.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Violation of the unique identification requirement in storage or deletion typically causes violation of idempotence.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Similarly, PUT and DELETE requests with nonspecific criteria may result in different outcomes depending on the state of the system – for example, a request to delete the most recent record.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In each case, subsequent executions will further modify the state of the system, so they are not idempotent.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In event stream processing, idempotence refers to the ability of a system to produce the same outcome, even if the same file, event or message is received more than once.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In a load–store architecture, instructions that might possibly cause a page fault are idempotent.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] So if a page fault occurs, the operating system can load the page from disk and then simply re-execute the faulted instruction.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In a processor where such instructions are not idempotent, dealing with page faults is much more complex.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] When reformatting output, pretty-printing is expected to be idempotent.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In other words, if the output is already "pretty", there should be nothing to do for the pretty-printer.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] In service-oriented architecture (SOA), a multiple-step orchestration process composed entirely of idempotent steps can be replayed without side-effects if any part of that process fails.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Many operations that are idempotent often have ways to "resume" a process if it is interrupted – ways that finish much faster than starting all over from the beginning.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] For example, resuming a file transfer, synchronizing files, creating a software build, installing an application and all of its dependencies with a package manager, etc.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Applied examples that many people could encounter in their day-to-day lives include elevator call buttons and crosswalk buttons.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] The initial activation of the button moves the system into a requesting state, until the request is satisfied.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Subsequent activations of the button between the initial activation and the request being satisfied have no effect, unless the system is designed to adjust the time for satisfying the request based on the number of activations.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] Similarly, the elevator "close" button may be pressed many times to the same effect as once, since the doors close on a fixed schedule – unless the "open" button is pressed.
[src:api-versioning/idempotence] The "open" button is not idempotent, because each press adds further delay.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] REST has been employed throughout the software industry to create stateless, reliable, web-based applications.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The term *representational state transfer* was introduced and defined in 2000 by computer scientist Roy Fielding in his doctoral dissertation.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] It means that a server will respond with the representation of a resource (today, it will most often be an HTML document) and that resource will contain hypermedia links that can be followed to make the state of the system change.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] Any such request will in turn receive the representation of a resource, and so on.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] An important consequence is that the only identifier that needs to be known is the identifier of the first resource requested, and all other identifiers will be discovered.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] This means that those identifiers can change without the need to inform the client beforehand and that client and server must be inherently loosely coupled.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The Web began to enter everyday use in 1993–1994, when websites for general use started to become available.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] At the time, only a fragmented description existed of the Web's architecture, and there was pressure within the community to agree on a standard for the Web interface protocols.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] For instance, several experimental extensions had been added to the communication protocol (HTTP) to support proxies, and more extensions were being proposed, but there was a need for a formal Web architecture with which to evaluate the impact of these changes.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The W3C and IETF working groups together started work on creating formal descriptions of the Web's three primary standards: URI, HTTP, and HTML.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] Fielding defined REST in his 2000 PhD dissertation "Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures" at UC Irvine.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] To create the REST architectural style, Fielding identified the requirements that apply when creating a world-wide network-based application, such as the need for a low entry barrier to enable global adoption.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] He also surveyed many existing architectural styles for network-based applications, identifying which features are shared with other styles, such as caching and client–server features, and those which are unique to REST, such as the concept of resources.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] Fielding was trying to both categorise the existing architecture of the current implementation and identify which aspects should be considered central to the behavioural and performance requirements of the Web.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] By their nature, architectural styles are independent of any specific implementation, and while REST was created as part of the development of the Web standards, the implementation of the Web does not obey every constraint in the REST architectural style.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] Mismatches can occur due to ignorance or oversight, but the existence of the REST architectural style means that they can be identified before they become standardised.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] For example, Fielding identified the embedding of session information in URIs as a violation of the constraints of REST which can negatively affect shared caching and server scalability.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] HTTP cookies also violate REST constraints because they can become out of sync with the browser's application state, making them unreliable; they also contain opaque data that can be a concern for privacy and security.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style is designed for network-based applications, specifically client-server applications.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] But more than that, it is designed for Internet-scale usage, so the coupling between the *user agent* (client) and the *origin server* must be as loose as possible to facilitate large-scale adoption.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The REST architectural style defines six guiding constraints.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] When these constraints are applied to the system architecture, it gains desirable non-functional properties, such as performance, scalability, simplicity, modifiability, visibility, portability, and reliability.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] The uniform interface constraint is fundamental to the design of any RESTful system.
[src:api-versioning/representational-state-transfer] It simplifies and decouples the architecture, which enables each part to evolve independently.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.8.1, 1.9.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.8, 1.81, 1.82.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added or for marketing purposes.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Version numbers are often used to identify copies of a software product and compare them against another copy in a collaborative version control system.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Within software development teams, version control is used to keep track of incrementally-different versions of information in order to be able to roll any changes back.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Modern computer software is often tracked using two different software versioning schemes: an internal version number, which may be incremented many times in a single day, and a release version, which typically changes far less often.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Historically, file numbers were especially used in public administration and corporations to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This practice was introduced to computer files for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX file system for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a standardized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy, which is particularly useful when using software libraries, frameworks, and command-line applications.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] File numbers were used especially in public administration, as well as companies, to uniquely identify files or cases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For computer files this practice was introduced for the first time with MIT's ITS file system, later the TENEX filesystem for the PDP-10 in 1972.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Later lists of files including their versions were added, and dependencies amongst them.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Linux distributions like Debian, with its dpkg, early on created package management software which could resolve dependencies between their packages.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Debian's first try was that a package knew other packages which depended on it.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] From 1994 on this idea was inverted, so a package that knew the packages it needed.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] When installing a package, dependency resolution was used to automatically calculate the packages needed as well, and install them with the desired package.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] To facilitate upgrades, minimum package versions were introduced.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Thus the numbering scheme needed to tell which version was newer than the required one.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In sequence-based software versioning schemes, each software release is assigned a unique identifier that consists of one or more sequences of numbers or letters.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This is the extent of the commonality; schemes vary widely in areas such as the number of sequences, the attribution of meaning to individual sequences, and the means of incrementing the sequences.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In some schemes, sequence-based identifiers are used to convey the significance of changes between releases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Semantic versioning (aka SemVer) is a widely adopted version scheme that encodes a version by a three-part version number (Major.Minor.Patch), an optional prerelease tag, and an optional build meta tag.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In this scheme, risk and functionality are the measures of significance.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Breaking changes are indicated by increasing the major number (high risk); new, non-breaking features increment the minor number (medium risk); and all other non-breaking changes increment the patch number (lowest risk).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The presence of a prerelease tag (-alpha, -beta) indicates substantial risk, as does a major number of zero (0.y.z), which is used to indicate a work-in-progress that may contain any level of potentially breaking changes (highest risk).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] As an example of inferring compatibility from a SemVer version, software which relies on version 2.1.5 of an API is compatible with version 2.2.3, but not necessarily with 3.2.4.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A fourth number may also be used to denote the software build, as was the case for Adobe Flash.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some companies also include the build date and letters and other characters, such as Lotus 1-2-3 Release 1a.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Developers may choose to jump multiple minor versions at a time to indicate that significant features have been added, but are not enough to warrant incrementing a major version number; for example, Internet Explorer 5 from 5.1 to 5.5 or Adobe Photoshop 5 to 5.5.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A different approach is to use the *major* and *minor* numbers along with an alphanumeric string denoting the release type, e.g.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A software release train using this approach might look like 0.5, 0.6, 0.7, 0.8, 0.9 → 1.0b1, 1.0b2 (with some fixes), 1.0b3 (with more fixes) → 1.0rc1 (if it is stable *enough*), 1.0rc2 (if more bugs are found) → 1.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] It is a common practice in this scheme to lock out new features and breaking changes during the release candidate phases and, for some teams, even betas are locked down to bug fixes only, to ensure convergence on the target release.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Again, in these examples, the definition of what constitutes a "major" as opposed to a "minor" change is entirely subjective and up to the author, as is what defines a "build", or how a "revision" differs from a "minor" change.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] : The most recent interface number that the library implements.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] : The implementation number of the current interface.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] : The difference between the newest and oldest interfaces that the library implements.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] : others may use a different meaning or simply ignore it.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A similar problem of relative change significance and versioning nomenclature exists in book publishing, where edition numbers or names can be chosen based on varying criteria.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In most proprietary software, the first released version of a software product has version 1.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some projects use the major version number to indicate incompatible releases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Two examples are Apache Portable Runtime (APR) and the FarCry CMS.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Often programmers write new software to be backward compatible.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For example, IBM z/OS is designed to work properly with 3 consecutive major versions of the operating system running in the same sysplex.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This enables people who run a high availability computer cluster to keep most of the computers up and running while one machine at a time is shut down, upgraded, and restored to service.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Often packet headers and file format include a version number – sometimes the same as the version number of the software that wrote it; other times a "protocol version number" independent of the software version number.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The code to handle old deprecated protocols and file formats is often seen as cruft.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Software in the experimental stage (alpha or beta) often uses a zero in the first ("major") position of the sequence to designate its status.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] However, this scheme is only useful for the early stages, not for upcoming releases with established software where the version number has already progressed past 0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The two purely numeric forms remove the special logic required to handle the comparison of "alpha < beta < rc < no prefix" as found in semantic versioning, at the cost of clarity.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Most free and open-source software packages, including MediaWiki, treat versions as a series of individual numbers, separated by periods, with a progression such as 1.7.0, 1.8.0, 1.8.1, 1.9.0, 1.10.0, 1.11.0, 1.11.1, 1.11.2, and so on.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] On the other hand, some software packages identify releases by decimal numbers: 1.7, 1.8, 1.81, 1.82, 1.9, etc.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Decimal versions were common in the 1980s, for example with NetWare, DOS, and Microsoft Windows, but even in the 2000s have been for example used by Opera and Movable Type.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In the decimal scheme, 1.81 is the minor version following 1.8, while maintenance releases (i.e. bug fixes only) may be denoted with an alphabetic suffix, such as 1.81a or 1.81b.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The standard GNU version numbering scheme is major.minor.revision, but Emacs is a notable example using another scheme where the major number (1) was dropped and a *user site* revision was added which is always zero in original Emacs packages but increased by distributors.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Similarly, Debian package numbers are prefixed with an optional "epoch", which is used to allow the versioning scheme to be changed.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In some cases, developers may decide to reset the major version number.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This is sometimes used to denote a new development phase being released.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For example, *Minecraft* Alpha ran from version 1.0.0 to 1.2.6, and when Beta was released, it reset the major version number and ran from 1.0 to 1.8.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Once the game was fully released, the major version number again reset to 1.0.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some projects use negative version numbers.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] One example is the SmartEiffel compiler which started from −1.0 and counted upwards to 0.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] To ease sorting, some software packages represent each component of the *major.minor.release* scheme with a fixed width.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Perl represents its version numbers as a floating-point number; for example, Perl's 5.8.7 release can also be represented as 5.008007.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This allows a theoretical version of 5.8.10 to be represented as 5.008010.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Other software packages pack each segment into a fixed bit width; for example, on Microsoft Windows, version number 6.3.9600.16384 would be represented as hexadecimal 0x0006000325804000.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The floating-point scheme breaks down if any segment of the version number exceeds 999; a packed-binary scheme employing 16 bits apiece breaks down after 65535.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Between the 1.0 and the 2.6.x series, the Linux kernel used odd minor version numbers to denote development releases and even minor version numbers to denote stable releases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For example, Linux 2.3 was a development family of the second major design of the Linux kernel, and Linux 2.4 was the stable release family that Linux 2.3 matured into.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] After the minor version number in the Linux kernel is the release number, in ascending order; for example, Linux 2.4.0 → Linux 2.4.22.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Since the 2004 release of the 2.6 kernel, Linux no longer uses this system, and has a much shorter release cycle.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The same odd-even system is used by some other software with long release cycles, such as Node.js up to version 0.12 as well as WineHQ.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Many projects use a date-based versioning scheme called **Calendar Versioning** (aka **CalVer**).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Ubuntu is one example of a project using calendar versioning; Ubuntu 18.04, for example, was released in April 2018.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This has the advantage of being easily relatable to development schedules and support timelines.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some video games also use date as versioning, for example the arcade game *Street Fighter EX*.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] At startup it displays the version number as a date plus a region code, for example *961219 ASIA*.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] When using dates in versioning, for instance, file names, it is common to use the ISO 8601 scheme *YYYY-MM-DD*, as this is easily string-sorted in increasing or decreasing order.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The Wine project formerly used a date versioning scheme, which used the year followed by the month followed by the day of the release; for example, "Wine 20040505".
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The earliest development builds of *Minecraft* had a similar version formatting, but instead used DDHHMM, for example rd-131655 was created on the 13th (of May 2009) at 16:21.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Microsoft Office build numbers are an encoded date: the first two digits indicate the number of months that have passed from the January of the year in which the project started (with each major Office release being a different project), while the last two digits indicate the day of that month.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] So 3419 is the 19th day of the 34th month after the month of January of the year the project started.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Other examples that identify versions by year include Adobe Illustrator 88 and WordPerfect Office 2003.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] When a year is used to denote version, it is generally for marketing purposes, and an actual version number also exists.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For example, Windows 95 is internally versioned as MS-DOS 7.00 and Windows 4.00; likewise, Windows 2000 is internally versioned as NT 5.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some software producers use different schemes to denote releases of their software.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The Debian project uses a major/minor versioning scheme for releases of its operating system but uses code names from the movie *Toy Story* during development to refer to stable, unstable, and testing releases.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] BLAG Linux and GNU features very large version numbers: major releases have numbers such as 50000 and 60000, while minor releases increase the number by 1 (e.g.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Alpha and beta releases are given decimal version numbers slightly less than the major release number, such as 19999.00071 for alpha 1 of version 20000, and 29999.50000 for beta 2 of version 30000.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Urbit uses *Kelvin versioning* (named after the absolute Kelvin temperature scale): software versions start at a high number and count down to version 0, at which point the software is considered finished and no further modifications are made.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In conjunction with the various versioning schemes listed above, a system for denoting prerelease versions is generally used, as the program makes its way through the stages of the software release life cycle.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Programs that are in an early stage are often called "alpha" software, after the first letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] After they mature but are not yet ready for release, they may be called "beta" software, after the second letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Generally alpha software is tested by developers only, while beta software is distributed for community testing.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some systems use numerical versions less than 1 (such as 0.9), to suggest their approach toward a final "1.0" release.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This is a common convention in open source software.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] However, if the prerelease version is for an existing software package (e.g. version 2.5), then an "a" or "alpha" may be appended to the version number.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] So the alpha version of the 2.5 release might be identified as 2.5a or 2.5.a.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Version numbers are used in practical terms by the consumer, or client, to identify or compare their copy of the software product against another copy, such as the newest version released by the developer.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For the programmer or company, versioning is often used on a revision-by-revision basis, where individual parts of the software are compared and contrasted with newer or older revisions of those same parts, often in a collaborative version control system.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In the 21st century, more programmers started to use a formalized version policy, such as the semantic versioning policy.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The purpose of such policies is to make it easier for other programmers to know when code changes are likely to break things they have written.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Such policies are especially important for software libraries and frameworks, but may also be very useful for command-line applications (which may be called from other applications) and for other applications (which may be scripted and/or extended by third parties).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A **software release train** is a form of software release schedule in which a number of distinct series of versioned software releases for multiple products are released as a number of different "trains" on a regular schedule.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Generally, for each product line, a number of different release trains are running at a given time, with each train moving from initial release to eventual maturity and retirement on a planned schedule.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Users may experiment with a newer release train before adopting it for production, allowing them to experiment with newer, "raw", releases early, while continuing to follow the previous train's point releases for their production systems prior to moving to the new release train as it becomes mature.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Cisco's IOS software platform used a release train schedule with many distinct trains for many years.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] More recently, a number of other platforms including Firefox and Fenix for Android, Eclipse, LibreOffice, Ubuntu, Fedora, Python, digiKam and VMware have adopted the release train model.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Software may have an "internal" version number which differs from the version number shown in the product name (and which typically follows version numbering rules more consistently).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Windows 10 was initially intended to be NT 6.4, as the earliest Technical Preview build shared to the public is numbered 6.4.9841.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] However, that did not last as the version of Windows 10 was quickly artificially increased to 10.0 to align with the commercial name, resulting in the first released version of the operating system being numbered 10.0.10240.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Note, however, that Windows NT is only on its fifth major revision, as its first release was numbered 3.1 (to match the then-current Windows release number) and the Windows 10 launching made a version leap from 6.3 to 10.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A relatively common practice is to make major jumps in version numbers for marketing reasons.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Sometimes software vendors just bypass the 1.0 release or quickly release a release with a subsequent version number because 1.0 software is considered by many customers too immature to trust with production deployments.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For example, as in the case of dBase II, a product is launched with a version number that implies that it is more mature than it is.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Other times version numbers are increased to match those of competitors.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This can be seen in many examples of product version numbering by Microsoft, America Online, Sun Solaris, Java Virtual Machine, SCO Unix, WordPerfect.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Microsoft Access jumped from version 2.0 to version 7.0, to match the version number of Microsoft Word.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Another example of keeping up with competitors is when Slackware Linux jumped from version 4 to version 7 in 1999.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This approach, panned by many because it breaks the semantic significance of the sections of the version number, has been adopted by an increasing number of vendors including Mozilla (for Firefox) and Google (for Google Chrome).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Sun also dropped the first digit for Solaris, where Solaris 2.8 (or 2.9) is referred to as Solaris 8 (or 9) in marketing materials.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A similar jump took place with the Asterisk open-source PBX construction kit in the early 2010s, whose project leads announced that the current version 1.8.x would soon be followed by version 10.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The free-software and open source communities tend to release software early and often.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Initial versions are numbers less than 1, with these 0.x version used to convey that the software is incomplete and not reliable enough for general release or usable in its current state.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Backward-incompatible changes are common with 0.x versions.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Version 1.0 is used as a major milestone, indicating that the software has at least all major features plus functions the developers wanted to get into that version, and is considered reliable enough for general release.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] A good example of this is the Linux kernel, which was first released as version 0.01 in 1991, and took until 1994 to reach version 1.0.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The developers of the arcade game emulator MAME do not ever intend to release a version 1.0 of the program because there will always be more arcade games to emulate and thus the project can never be truly completed.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Accordingly, version 0.99 was followed by version 0.100.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The Python Software Foundation has published PEP 440 – Version Identification and Dependency Specification, outlining their own flexible scheme, that defines an epoch segment, a release segment, prerelease and post-release segments and a development release segment.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] TeX has an idiosyncratic version numbering system, an unusual feature invented by its developer Donald Knuth.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Since version 3.1, updates have been indicated by adding an extra digit at the end, so that the version number asymptotically approaches the number π, so 3.14 effectively means 3.2 in semantic versioning.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] (This is a form of unary numbering; the version number is the number of digits.) Since 2021, the version number has been 3.141592653.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This is a reflection of TeX being very stable, and only minor updates are anticipated.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] TeX developer Donald Knuth has stated that the *"absolutely final change (to be made after [his] death)"* will be to change the version number to π, at which point all remaining bugs will become permanent features.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In a similar way, the version number of Metafont asymptotically approaches Euler's number, e.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Metafont was also devised by Donald Knuth as a companion to his TeX typesetting system.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] During the era of the classic Mac OS, minor version numbers rarely went beyond ".1".
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] When they did, they usually jumped straight to ".5", suggesting the release was "more significant".
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Thus, "8.5" was marketed as its own release, representing "Mac OS 8 and a half", and 8.6 effectively meant "8.5.1".
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Mac OS X departed from this trend, in large part because "X" (the Roman numeral for 10) was in the name of the product.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] As a result, all versions of OS X began with the number 10.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The first major release of OS X was given the version number 10.0, but the next major release was not 11.0.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Instead, it was numbered 10.1, followed by 10.2, 10.3, and so on for each subsequent major release.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Thus the 11th major version of OS X was labeled "10.10".
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Even though the "X" was dropped from the name as of macOS 10.12, this numbering scheme continued through macOS 10.15.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Under the "X"-based versioning scheme, the third number (instead of the second) denoted a minor release, and additional updates below this level, as well as updates to a given major version of OS X coming after the release of a new major version, were titled Supplemental Updates.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The Roman numeral X was concurrently leveraged for marketing purposes across multiple product lines.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Both QuickTime and Final Cut Pro jumped from version 7 directly to version 10, QuickTime X and Final Cut Pro X.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Like Mac OS X itself, the products were not upgrades to previous versions, but brand-new programs.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] As with OS X, major releases for these programs incremented the second digit and minor releases were denoted using a third digit.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The "X" was dropped from Final Cut's name with the release of macOS 11.0 (see below), and QuickTime's branding became moot when the framework was deprecated in favor of AVFoundation in 2011 (the program for playing QuickTime video was only named QuickTime Player from the start).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Apple's next macOS release, provisionally numbered 10.16, was officially announced as macOS 11 at WWDC in June 2020, and released in November 2020.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The following macOS version, macOS Monterey, was released in October 2021 and bumped its major version number to 12.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In June 2025, Apple announced an unified versioning scheme, using the year next to the release date, similar to model years in vehicles.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The versions that were released in the fall of 2025 are iOS 26, macOS 26, iPadOS 26, tvOS 26, watchOS 26 and visionOS 26.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The Microsoft Windows operating system was first labelled with standard version numbers for Windows 1.01 through Windows 3.2.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] After this Microsoft excluded the version number from the product name.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] For Windows 95 (version 4.0), Windows 98 (4.10) and Windows 2000 (5.0), year of the release was included in the product title.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] After Windows 2000, Microsoft created the Windows Server family which continued the year-based style with a difference: For minor releases, Microsoft suffixed "R2" to the title, e.g., Windows Server 2008 R2 (version 6.1).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] This style had remained consistent to this date.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The client versions of Windows however did not adopt a consistent style.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] First, they received names with arbitrary alphanumeric suffixes as with Windows Me (4.90), Windows XP (5.1), and Windows Vista (6.0).
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Then, once again Microsoft adopted incremental numbers in the title, but this time, they were not versioning numbers; the version numbers of Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows 8.1 are respectively 6.1, 6.2 and 6.3.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] In Windows 10, the version number leaped to 10.0 and subsequent updates to the OS only incremented build number (which is date-based) and update build revision (UBR) number.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] The successor of Windows 10, Windows 11, was released on October 5, 2021.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Despite being named "11", the new Windows release did not bump its major version number to 11.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Instead, it stayed at the same version number of 10.0, used by Windows 10.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Some computer file systems, such as the OpenVMS Filesystem, also keep versions for files.
[src:api-versioning/software-versioning] Technical drawing and CAD software files may also use some kind of primitive versioning number to keep track of changes.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A **web API** is an application programming interface (API) for either a web server or a web browser.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] As a web development concept, it can be related to a web application's client side (including any web frameworks being used).
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed **endpoints** to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A server API (SAPI) is not considered a server-side web API, unless it is publicly accessible by a remote web application.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A client-side web API is a programmatic interface to extend functionality within a web browser or other HTTP client.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Originally these were most commonly in the form of native plug-in browser extensions however most newer ones target standardized JavaScript bindings.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The Mozilla Foundation created their WebAPI specification which is designed to help replace native mobile applications with HTML5 applications.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Google created their Native Client architecture which is designed to help replace insecure native plug-ins with secure native sandboxed extensions and applications.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] They have also made this portable by employing a modified LLVM AOT compiler.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A server-side web API consists of one or more publicly exposed *endpoints* to a defined request–response message system, typically expressed in JSON or XML.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The web API is exposed most commonly by means of an HTTP-based web server.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Endpoints are important aspects of interacting with server-side web APIs, as they specify where resources can be accessed by third-party software.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Usually the access is via a URI to which HTTP requests are posted, and from which the response is thus expected.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Web APIs may be public or private, the latter of which requires an *access token*.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Endpoints need to be static, otherwise the correct functioning of software that interacts with them cannot be guaranteed.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] If the location of a resource changes (and with it the endpoint) then previously written software will break, as the required resource can no longer be found at the same place.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] As API providers still want to update their web APIs, many have introduced a versioning system in the URI that points to an endpoint.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Web 2.0 Web APIs often use machine-based interactions such as REST and SOAP.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] RESTful web APIs use HTTP methods to access resources via URL-encoded parameters, and use JSON or XML to transmit data.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] By contrast, SOAP protocols are standardized by the W3C and mandate the use of XML as the payload format, typically over HTTP.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Furthermore, SOAP-based Web APIs use XML validation to ensure structural message integrity, by leveraging the XML schemas provisioned with WSDL documents.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] A WSDL document accurately defines the XML messages and transport bindings of a Web service.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Server-side web APIs are interfaces for the outside world to interact with the business logic.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] For many companies this internal business logic and the intellectual property associated with it are what distinguishes them from other companies, and potentially what gives them a competitive edge.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] They do not want this information to be exposed.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] However, in order to provide a web API of high quality, there *needs* to be a sufficient level of documentation.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] One API provider that not only provides documentation, but also links to it in its error messages is Twilio.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] However, there are now directories of popular documented server-side web APIs.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The number of available web APIs has grown consistently over the past years, as businesses realize the growth opportunities associated with running an open platform, that any developer can interact with.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] ProgrammableWeb tracks over 24000 Web APIs that were available in 2022, up from 105 in 2005.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] There are few major software applications/services that do not offer some form of web API.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] One of the most common forms of interacting with these web APIs is via embedding external resources, such as tweets, Facebook comments, YouTube videos, etc.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] In fact there are very successful companies, such as Disqus, whose main service is to provide embeddable tools, such as a feature-rich comment system.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Any website of the TOP 100 Alexa Internet ranked websites uses APIs and/or provides its own APIs, which is a very distinct indicator for the prodigious scale and impact of web APIs as a whole.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] As the number of available web APIs has grown, open source tools have been developed to provide more sophisticated search and discovery.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] APIs.json provides a machine-readable description of an API and its operations, and the related project APIs.io offers a searchable public listing of APIs based on the APIs.json metadata format.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Many companies and organizations rely heavily on their Web API infrastructure to serve their core business clients.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] In 2014 Netflix received around 5 billion API requests, most of them within their private API.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Many governments collect a lot of data, and some governments are now opening up access to this data.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The interfaces through which this data is typically made accessible are web APIs.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Web APIs allow for data, such as "budget, public works, crime, legal, and other agency data" to be accessed by any developer in a convenient manner.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] An example of a popular web API is the Astronomy Picture of the Day API operated by the American space agency NASA.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] It is a server-side API used to retrieve photographs of space or other images of interest to astronomers, and metadata about the images.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The documentation states that this endpoint accepts GET requests.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] It requires one piece of information from the user, an API key, and accepts several other optional pieces of information.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Such pieces of information are known as *parameters*.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The parameters for this API are written in a format known as a query string, which is separated by a question mark character (`?`) from the endpoint.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] An ampersand (`&`) separates the parameters in the query string from each other.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Together, the endpoint and the query string form a URL that determines how the API will respond.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] This URL is also known as a *query* or an *API call*.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] In the below example, two parameters are transmitted (or *passed*) to the API via the query string.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The first is the required API key and the second is an optional parameter — the date of the photograph requested.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Visiting the above URL in a web browser will initiate a GET request, calling the API and showing the user a result, known as a *return value* or as a *return*.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] This API returns JSON, a type of data format intended to be understood by computers, but which is somewhat easy for a human to read as well.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The above API return has been reformatted so that names of JSON data items, known as *keys*, appear at the start of each line.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] Although this API can be called by an end user with a web browser (as in this example) it is intended to be called automatically by software or by computer programmers while writing software.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] JSON is intended to be parsed by a computer program, which would extract the URL of the photograph and the other metadata.
[src:api-versioning/web-api] The resulting photo could be embedded in a website, automatically sent via text message, or used for any other purpose envisioned by a software developer.
